column2: i had no idea how relevant it would be to the #metoo movement and the drama unfolding around kavanaugh. this victorian melodrama centers around the teenage peasant tess
column3: and how her rape by the scoundrel alec derails her entire life. the novel is enraging at times because even though tess is the victim she is blamed for her rape while her rapist goes free. it truly embodies the boys will be boys mentality and that women who are raped are to blame. what is even more heart wrenching is that we really haven't advanced that much in our ideas about rape since the victorians. we still blame the victim and re-victimize her
column4: and it still ruins the woman's life much more than the man's even if she reports it. in many ways i see kavanaugh as the modern equivalent of alec d' urberville... an entitled scoundrel who known for this behavior and it was tolerated due to his white rich status.

column2: polanski's adaptation of the novel is very much rape apologetic. he turns the creepiness and stalking nature of alec into a overzealous ex lover. even though criterion did an amazing job with this blueray set and the disks are beautiful
column3: i just can't abide the movie for that reason.

column2: ice nine kills has an amazing song based on the novel titled tess-timony. highly recommend listening to it.

a skin of earlier times shadowed and lit.
a piece of a vessel broken in derangement.
the cicada has long since buzzed the summer song
and now to us it is later and we still know our world is wrong.
would it be better for a misogynistic man to strip off his abusive skin?
could the broken shards of past we walk on be swept into a bin?
were it that easy we should make it so
but of course there are humans who need to grow.

column1: 337042;instagram;2018-09-29 18:56:44;FALSE;this is a hard post for me to make. however
column2: i feel that it is crucial at this time in history to share my story. when i was 15 and a sophomore i dated an 18 year old senior for a brief amount of time. one night we went bowling with some friends and on our way home he pulled over at a park and i asked to go home. he told me no and guilted me into staying. i said i was tired
column3: i said i had to be up early
column4: i said my mom wanted me home but he wouldn’t listen. i won’t go into the details of what happened next. but why didn’t i say anything? i didn’t know. he was my boyfriend
column6: the previous night he talked about his love of knives and how he had one in his car. so what else could i do? when i tried to break up with him he told me i wasn’t allowed to. after another week i finally found a way out of the relationship but he would stand at my locker
column7: make his friends talk to me and constantly text me. i don’t think i went to my locker for the next few weeks. he still occasionally pops up even after i’ve blocked him on everything and tries to guilt me into “helping” him. this month is the month we remember and stand with those who have encountered abusive relationships and we also stand with dr. ford and the rest of our sisters who have experienced sexual assault. this is the first time i am publicly acknowledging  that i too am a victim and a survivor. we are with you. we believe you. #metoo #believesurvivors #mterc2018;;en;#metoo

column1: 337045;instagram;2018-09-29 18:57:05;FALSE;i debated whether or not to post this
column2: but i am doing so because i think it’s important people realize they’re not alone. the past few days have been rough. there are an infinite number of reasons why survivors don’t report. it is an undeniable fallacy to conclude that not reporting=it didn’t happen. survivors also don’t owe anyone an explanation as to why they didn’t report initially unless it’s in a court of law. when a loved one musters the courage to tell  you they were assaulted
column5: realize this - they are often overcoming/trying to understand their own feelings of disbelief in what happened due to the societal narrative surrounding “what counts” and “well it was your fault anyway.” i couldn’t process what happened to me initially. i tried to tell my best friend
column6: and couldn’t. i couldn’t use the “r” word for literally years because that somehow made it more real. it affected my relationships
column7: i had adverse reactions to my attempts to tell confidants
column8: and i’ve listened to men in my life - many of whom i love dearly - express concern for each other over “false reports.” if you think reporting is easy
column9: please try to educate yourselves and take into consideration everything people go through in these circumstances. it is never easy. trauma is not something anyone can wrap their head around immediately. be compassionate

column1: i was 5 the first time i remember being sexually assaulted by someone in the family.  i kept it to myself until i was 15.  when i shared what happened my mother decided to stay married to the creep.  i left home at 17 so i never had to stay in that house ever again. i understand on a very  deep level this toxic victim blaming culture.  no one listened to me either.  many victims face being re-traumatized. the fact that most sexual assaults still go unreported is not an indication of whether it actually happened.  it's an indication of this sick culture that seeks to protect the predators. enough is enough.
my abusers name is james edward finlay. he is now 68 and he currently lives at 33 plymouth avenue in swampscott
column2: ma.  i contacted the police three times both in hingham
column4: ma to pursue justice and got nowhere. i was told i needed to provide the specific dates and times when the childhood abuse happened. how at age 15 can someone recall dates when they were traumatized at age 5
column7: etc? i didn't know what a calendar was ffs. the system is definitely focused on protecting the abusers.  i know for a fact that he sexually assaulted other children after me. 😕

column1: i find the #metoo movement to be triggering as fuck. i’m in awe of its power
column2: but it’s both absolutely necessary for our society and extremely painful
column3: in equal measures. on one hand
column4: i’m grateful for the cleansing power of the truth
column5: and i’m inspired by the strength it takes my fellow survivors to gaze upon the the truth
column6: especially in front of other people and especially when they’re directly confronting those who have harmed them. but on the other hand
column7: reading/hearing about the trauma of others makes me miserable because it forces me to gaze upon my own truth which leads to a self-hate landslide from which recovery can feel impossible. and as much as i anticipate coming to terms with ‘the things i hate thinking about’ when i’m meditating or practicing yoga
column8: i’m much less prepared to deal with my baggage when i’m innocently scrolling through social media feeds.

column1: when i watched dr. ford’s testimony
column2: all i could think was “i can’t believe she’s brave enough to talk about this in front of other people.” i was in awe. spellbound. talking about it on the international stage must be like living a nightmare. i wouldn’t know
column3: as i can’t bring myself to do the same because my memories both horrify and embarrass me. and i’m well aware that i need not be embarrassed but that doesn’t make the emotions any less real.

column1: i’m fascinated by the ways in which we all view/experience/hold our trauma. i wish sensitivity and empathy were considered as valuable as anger. surviving is more than just fodder for content.

column1: 337077;instagram;2018-09-29 19:12:24;FALSE;"47 years ago i was sexually assaulted at gunpoint.
when i reported the event to the police  i was not believed
column3: and humiliated. i was told i had ‘asked for it’ even though i was held hostage by my attacker for hours

column1: i was made to feel ashamed and embarrassed. as a result i blamed myself and internalized my pain and trauma and suffered in silence for decades.

it wasn’t until i got the help i needed many years later and began sharing my story with other survivors that the true healing began. i found a strength and power inside of myself that i didn’t know i had. i became a ‘thriver’ instead of just a survivor.
i never thought i would live to see the day of the #metoo movement.
to all of the brave women who have come forward i want to thank you.
keep sharing. there is power in our numbers to finally make a true cultural shift and to change the climate of fear
column3: and darkness that we have lived in.  let’s use our voices to empower those who are not yet ready to use their own and help lift others up out of the darkness and into the light of hope and love. it is never
column4: ever your fault and you are not alone💪🏼❤️

column1: i have reported. i began by reporting.
the first time. with the first partner.

column2: it's been too many times with too many people.

column1: now i don't report because i dont want to be the one on the pyre for disrupting a scene anymore.
because i had to hear shit like ""i just couldn't see ____ doing that"" from other strong
or uncomfortable silence from every male counterpart i told.
because every apology was recanted and demanding the truth became too disruptive for my life.
because i feel great shame for having a habitual past.
because i feel great blame for consistently being a recipient to this.

because the irony that i challenge others to be more vocal about their mental health journey while remaining quiet about my domestic violence issues is not lost on me and in fact makes me not want to mention the latter that much more profusely.
but i have to say something.
so this is what i do want to report:
there exists a new beginning after spousal abuse.
there is a new life after sexual assault.
and it is beyond the reach of the abuser who controls everything around you.
and it is a scary and fulfilling battle to get there.
there is a way through the dark madness in your head and in your life.
you don't have to be bound by your past.
you don't even have to be bound by your present.
you deserve to find your heart again
column2: not to have it toyed with and held as collateral damage by somebody who is supposed to love you.

column1: there are ways to get to a safe space and people who will help bring you there if that's where you wish to go.
it is time to be strong.
be brave. i already know you are.

column4: of having a daughter. i imagined all these life lessons i would teach my child and the kind of adult our baby would grow up to be. in my eyes
column5: raising a boy would have been easier. you teach your son to be empathetic
column8: respectful- you teach your son about consent. then you send him into the world knowing that you gave him the tools to survive and create thriving
column10: deep relationships. with a daughter you do all those same things and then you send her into the world and you hope... hope that she never has to experience sexual harassment
column13: rape. it's like i'm living my deepest fear- we as parents could do everything ""right""
column15: and yet she is a female in a society that chooses not to believe females. i was talking to a family member yesterday

column1: 337097;instagram;2018-09-29 19:28:17;FALSE;"i was in 7th grade the first time i experienced sexual assult. the boys in my class thought it would be funny to shove sticks up girls skirts and i was one of them. these same boys also pressured my best friends into doing other things and i finally spoke up and told our teachers. from that day on
column2: i was ridiculed and rejected by the girls and boys alike so much to the point that i wanted to kill myself and finally dropped out of my class to be homeschooled. i was in 7th grade.

column1: this week has been overwhelming for many of us. seeing so many people share their stories of sexual violence has been both empowering and also very upsetting. i read one account in particular that was hauntingly similar to my story of being raped 2 years ago. in seeing all of these stories emerge
column2: i am recognizing how silent i have been about this most recent experience of sexual assault. maybe it is because i never want to hear from the person who raped me again
column3: and i worry that publicly naming him may lead to him contacting me. maybe it is also because i have struggled to believe myself and to not blame myself for the assault. i don’t have much more to say
column4: except that i feel the weight of silence.

column1: the person in this image does not see themselves as guilty or disgusting or weak. they are boldly protecting themselves and they are looking towards the future with fierceness and curiosity. this figure is my hope for myself and for all survivors.

column1: 337112;instagram;2018-09-29 19:31:55;FALSE;"“the great thing about faith in god is that it keeps a man undisturbed in the midst of disturbance.”

speaking truth is difficult. even as i write this my heart is pounding and i want no harm to come to people i love and unfortunately these men all have families. i have friends on social media from since i was a small child. i never want to indirectly cause pain for any of them
column2: through someone sharing this post. i also want to first and foremost
column3: honor god. he is my redeemer and has rewritten my story! praise him!! he keeps me undisturbed in the midst of disturbance!

column1: i was 3 years old. that’s my first memory of being sexually abused. my parents were getting married again and the ceremony was at our church elder’s home. their teenage son was watching me in his bedroom
column2: while a celebration of love happened in the living room. the moment is etched in my mind. i’ll not share the details
column3: those aren’t necessary. i was in my 30’s before i told anyone. there were neighbor men in the projects where i grew up who would also sexually abuse me for years. my mother sent me to borrow things from one of them and every time she did
column4: the man touched my body.  in the 6th grade  my school teacher would call me to his desk and talk to me while he slid his hand up the inside of my leg...i was 11 years old. i wore dresses every day
column5: that was because of our religion. i’ve never told anyone until today.

column2: 2 men who were meant to protect me
column3: sexually abused me.  it was devastating for me as a child. it altered my view
column5: but of men. i began to believe all men sexually abused children. there were girls in my life who spoke out against these men and were ostracized for saying anything
column6: made out to believe it was their fault or called a liar and manipulator...those men were wooed by those girls after-all.

column1: 337123;instagram;2018-09-29 19:35:24;FALSE;"even when we think we've healed something
column2: an experience is presented that seems to bring it all back up. does it mean we're back at square one and all our progress has vanished? no.

column1: we can learn to see this as an opportunity to heal different aspects of our trauma
column2: because it's really these neglected aspects that are causing the resonant experience of triggering.
i work with women (and a few men!)
column3: focused on healing. self-healing is my most intense passion.

column2: i've learned even more deeply to embrace flow. to say to myself ""it's ok that i'm not perfectly healed (that does not exist!) it's ok that i'm in pain. it's ok that i've neglected my trauma of sexual abuse because i was focused on deeply healing other personally more intense traumas."" i hear so many lovely people in this community talk about ""clearing"" experiences and energy as though we just burn some sage and boom! i've definitely used this term before too so it's all good. 😂 but we all know it's not like that.

column1: the truth is that things don't just ""clear""
column2: they heal. we have the ability to transmute energies of trauma and pain into love.

column1: am i healed? yes. am i still healing? yes.
embrace the pain. heart wide open.
love to you and thank you for being here. thank you for loving and healing yourself. through healing ourselves

column1: 337143;instagram;2018-09-29 19:46:35;FALSE;"i love this mug. i know it's a tad silly and doesn't do anything to make change. i mean
column2: what the hell does a mug have to do with feminism? especially when i'm the only one to see it. well
column4: it's a daily reminder of the realities of our world and that i must not become complacent. it's exhausting to be an advocate and there are many days i want to stick my head in the sand and ignore what's happening. but i'm fortunate to have this option. i am privileged via the color of my skin and economic status to be able to ignore suffering (and maybe even minimize my own). but my heart cannot and will not allow it. 💗 a feminist is one who supports ""the advocacy of women's rights on the grounds of political
column6: and economic equality to men."" i'd argue though that this should be ""all minorities' rights"" not just women's. 💗 the foundations of our society in america (and arguably the world) are rooted in a white patriarchal system that has encouraged and supported toxic masculinity while suppressing anyone that is an ""other."" what we're seeing happen now is an opposition to that system. and this isn't just about women and it isn't ""man bashing"" (unless you're one of one of the rapey ones...then i will absolutely bash you). the first self proclaimed feminist i met was an ex-boyfriend of mine
column7: even before i identified as such. he saw the injustice and refused to be apathetic towards it. 💗 the friction we're experiencing is uncomfortable. it's scary. but it's necessary. this country is hurting and these issues will continue to surface until something begins to change. #femenist #femenism #equality #progress #metoo #timesup #ibelieveher";;en;#femenist

337163;instagram;2018-09-29 19:58:49;FALSE;i’m still shaken by the hearings this week and in complete awe of dr. christine blasey ford. what an inspiration! 👊

column2: #metoo. the first times i traveled by myself
column3: i was 19 years old and then 20. i’ve never been sexually assaulted but there were some close calls. there were a few times when i was by myself
column4: at night. i had broken my own rule of not taking basic precaution and decided to go out by myself anyway. in one incident
column5: a taxi driver tried to grab my boobs. in another incident
column6: a smuck chased me down the road on his bike while two security guards observed and did nothing (they were guarding an atm machine). and there were many other incidents when a guy asked me the whereabouts of my boyfriend or husband. the audacity of a man allowing their woman to travel by herself!

column2: my knee jerk reaction (fight or flight) put me at risk and probably saved my life. what i learned was that these attackers are cowards or inebriated privileged males. they don’t have the skills to talk to women so they behave like beasts. i’ve been meditating for some time and i still have no compassion for you hijos de putas.

column1: to avoid putting heat on any country i’ll be vague and concede to the fact that most or all of these attacks happened in latin america; a continent plagued by machismo and theocracy. some of you know that i love latin america so much that those events have clearly not scared me away. i traveled latin america several times after and i even live in colombia today. so
as much as i hate to admit it
column2: those attacks and even the hissing have dwindled ever since i started traveling with james. i’ve also become a more sagacious traveler and still travel on my own every other month. so here’s my message to women aspiring to travel solo: go travel. stop making excuses and do it.

column1: 337173;instagram;2018-09-29 20:01:35;FALSE;"the odds have been stacked against our voice for far too long. the collective energy of women coming forward and telling the truth is powerful. and if you're sick and tired of seeing this on your feed... sorry (butnotsorry) we're only getting warmed up!! .
you see when women come forward to share their stories it gives other women the permission to share theirs.
women have been carrying the collective traumas of our past generations
column2: present day and deeply storing it in our bodies.

column1: when the #metoo movement started and i was hearing all the stories of women's sexual assualts
column2: i started to deep dive into memories of my own. memories of times where i had been date raped
column3: sexually assualted by a ""friend"" and many other inappropriate situations surfaced. i knew about these times but back then i thought that i did something wrong. i didn't say anything because i didn't want to make anyone uncomfortable. w.t.f?! .

column1: this has been a collective of traumas women have carried for lifetimes. we were taught to stay quiet.
that is changing. this powerful collective has triggered a lot of women in reflecting back in their own experiences and it gives us power to become louder about what we have been through.
so ladies tell your story. you're giving other women the permission to tell theirs and then the healing can begin. please tell your story. .
if i didn't hear those stories i would have been thinking that all those past experiences we're my fault and felt shame my whole entire life for that.

and if you need a sacred and safe place to share your story you can do so in my soul driven sisterhood (link is in my profile) ill be talking about how trauma effects our body all this week. we got ya ❤️

and if you need a sacred and safe place to share your story you can do so in my soul driven sisterhood (link is in my profile) ill be talking about how trauma effects our body all this week. we got ya ❤️

column1: girl of six purple her favorite color/
went with parents to their friends and neighbours/
came time to rest and take a nap/
older man said he too was tired and side by side he reached to give her a pat/
how many times must this occur //
when will we believe him or her// shes just a child afraid to say a word//
they're suppose to friends so maybe it's just her//
went to school and a teacher touches her during movies/
tells another teacher who just said not to worry/
he's done it before got a slap and returned in a hurry/
not enough staff  so their fear they together silently bury/
how many times must this occur//
when will we believe him or her//
she's just a child afraid to say a word//
he's the teacher again it must be her//
in high school another teacher makes inappropriate comments/
has her go out to his convertible car for books/
outside he tells of  divorcing his wife and how he likes her looks/
inside he brushed against her as he passed out the textbooks/
how many times must this occur//
when when we believe him or her//
she's still a child afraid to say a word//
another teacher it's got to be her//
eighteen now alone needing a job/
store opens round the corner from home owned by bob/
'older guy once again sexual comments come from his jaw/
fed up  shes tells him what he can do almost sticks ' n her craw/
how many times must this occur//
we must believe him or her//
no longer children but still afraid to say a word// now it's bosses and jobs are on the line for her//
women and children arent play things or toys/
speak up with me and please with me join/
this me too movement will disappear if we don't keep making noise/
*sexual harrassent isn't funny or harmless. obviously i remember everything after all these years. it must end now!

337203;instagram;2018-09-29 20:19:27;FALSE;sis, i pose no threat. the only one i’m in competition with is myself. girls need to be kinder to one another , understand one another, and support one another. having a strong woman tribe is necessary, empowering, and reassuring. ✊🏼 as women in a man’s world, we need to have each others’ backs. there are a lot of good men in this world, alhamdulillah. men who will support women and treat us with respect, loyalty, and love. thank you for making us feel special like we deserve. however, with that being said, there has always been a lot of bad men in this world as well and for generations, centuries, these bad men have always put us down subliminally. many times, they’ve pinned our own kind against each other. women have been set to compare themselves to each other since the beginning of time whether it’s because of looks, size, affairs, relationships, politics, violence, in the end we women end up suffering in these matters. based on insecurities women have developed related to trying to please a man or his views, women tend to turn on each other in many situations. today, it might be seen as just irresponsibility and jealousy. but it’s more than that— it’s systemic hate that’s been fed to us women for the longest time. accumulated via society, via media, via men themselves, and unfortunately via other women who adopted those negative thoughts and ways. strong women pose fears in these kinds of men. and let me tell you, many times, a group of strong women can rile up their insecurities like no other. it bruises their egos. why? i have no idea tbh. what i do know though is that if women were as close knit and supportive as these men who plot in their bat caves, we would be running the world already. it’s about time for a paradigm shift. speak up for your sisters, ladies. we all need that voice. #thehijabihooligan #girllove #metoo #webelieveher #justice #equality ❣️;;en;#thehijabihooligan, column1: the first time: i was 4 years old
again: because my bully was my mothers best friends child and i was told he’d stop bullying me when i stood up for myself.
and again: because although i was at a party with all my friends i thought the grouping of my breasts out of the blue was my fault for being at a party.
and again: because it was my partner that raped me and even though his friends knew he was abusing me
column2: they made sure to tell me it was none of their business and his friendship came before my abuse.

column1: and again: because he was a “friend” who non-stop pursued me until he was able to corner me and do what he wanted.
and now: because a medical professional violated me and i thought i was just supposed to deal with that part of being a woman.
this time: i. will. no. longer. be. silent.
i see you ladies! i hear you! i am with you! silence.no.more.

column1: 337234;instagram;2018-09-29 20:40:44;FALSE;"the past few days have brutally torn open scars for some of us. i'm saddened to learn that some
column3: turning their backs and even so far as to criticize what others are sharing on their own feeds. that it is all too personal and too painful to speak of. it's not nice
column5: or pretty. shut up! go back to the hole you crawled out of. make only happy art. share only sweet words. let me say first
column6: i feel deep gratitude for all of you who have offered support
column7: understanding and empathy. thank you! but i will never understand those who are so insular that they also believe this travesty that has played out publically is all born from some political agenda. i certainly didn't set the stage that is the reality we find ourselves in. that machine has been out of control for years because no one wanted to step up. i do not have answers. what i see are people who have been thrown into a darkness of pain and turmoil of body
column8: mind and soul and are reaching for the light and asking
column9: demanding to be seen because they are carrying things they should have never had to bear and are weary of doing so. that our world has become some sort of back alley
column10: political street fight that seems to encompass every aspect of our lives is not what motivates us; it is simply a reality of the times. i express myself openly to heal. sometimes those things are dark an unfathomable
column11: and sometimes it's about parties and goodness and love. if someone feels the need to use thier feed to thrash and scream i will support them regardless of who they are aligned with because for me
column14: i heal a bit more. but certain events
column15: certain horrors are seared into my psych
column16: into my very dna and the best i can do is anything i can to keep them at bay and while doing so

column1: 337245;instagram;2018-09-29 20:44:09;FALSE;"i had a beautiful and fun time participating in the mid-south pride parade & festival. there was so much unfiltered love in the air. i showed up today as an ally because i believe showing up for each other and stretching our personal boundaries is a major part of how we make change happen. i showed up with joy and love and support and with the statement “let me know what you need from me.” i showed up in the same way i want white people to show up for black lives matter events.
the same way i want american born people to march for immigrant rights and fight deportation.
the same way i want all religions to support muslims against bans and islamaphobia.
the same way i want men to believe #metoo and take responsibility to end rape culture.
the same way i want able bodied people to consider disabled people in the daily design of life.
the same way i want all united states citizens to stand with first nations and protect their water and their land.
i showed up. and i urge each of us to show up everyday.
and for my friends who identify as lgbtqia+
column2: thank you for making me a better person and teaching me what it means to be an ally.

column1: i believe you. i believe you because i know that quivering voice
column2: i know the humiliation of keeping a secret out of fear or even out of protection from my own perpetrator.

column1: i was also 15 (the first time). i wasn't able to escape. it took me years to even admit what happened. i had always thought rape happened violently in an alley where a stranger attacks you from behind and you're left in a heap next to garbage. no one had ever taught me otherwise. date rape was a brand new concept and one that hadn't been explained to me. i believed afterwards that if i tried hard enough to get him to like me it would suddenly be ok.
my assaulter was 21. i was 15. just turned 15 that summer. i had gone to a party
column4: i could barely walk. i naively trusted the people i was with. i took a walk into the woods with a man
column6: i remember him having his arm around my waist to help hold me up. i remember kissing him- i wanted to. i had a girlish crush on him. i remember feeling excited for a moment because i thought it meant he liked me too.

column1: i remember leaves in my hair and him being on top of me. i tried to sit up or protest but i could barely move. i was too drunk. i remember the smell of the pine trees and that i was having sex but hadn't recalled consenting
column2: i also hadn't recalled saying 'no'. i did try to sit up and protest but my body fell back into the carpeted forest floor.

column1: i remember hearing my friend call for me
column2: telling me it was time for us to leave
column3: she was worried and couldn't find me. i tried to sit up again. i tried to say i had to leave
column4: he told me everything would be ok
column5: that he would make sure i got home safely. i tried to call out to my friend. christine
column6: this is why your testimony hit me so hard. this is the exact reason i believe you. he put his hand over my mouth so i couldn't call back to my friend. i remember being confused and not really understanding what was happening. he held his hand over my mouth while i tried to yell my friend's name...(continued in comments)

column1: i have a tale to tell….

i was raped when i was 15 years old. i went on a date and got really drunk and high and told him no. it happened anyhow. i repeatedly said no. at the time i didn’t think that it was rape. everything i had seen in the media and such always portrayed it as something violent. he didn’t hurt me
column2: but he didn’t listen to me either.
i told my friend the story and she said
column3: “he raped you!” i still didn’t think it was in fact rape.

column1: the way we’re force fed a belief system. how were told to think and act. i also never thought it could happen to guys. i was young and naive and misinformed.
i remember the guy was worried that somehow my mom would find out and press charges.
i didn’t tell my mother until i was about 22 or so. i just remember her sighing and saying “well
column2: i’m sorry that happened to you.” and that was that.

column1: at 15 i was out but we didn’t discuss it. i was the rainbow elephant in the room.
i didn’t want to deal with my family and my sexuality. i even less wanted to deal with the fact that i was raped. since i was out in school i felt a magnifying glass was already on me.

column2: because i was scared. i stayed silent because i didn’t fully grasp what had happened to me. because i was confused about what was rape

column1: i still haven’t completely dealt with this past. it feels a million miles away. another lifetime. another me.
but that doesn’t diminish the fact that it happened.
never doubt anyone’s truth. never say that they were asking for it. believe them. comfort them. listen to their stories.
do not let fear take hold. be brave and tell your truths. don’t be made to feel like you’re the villain.
for too long i misconstrued what had happened to be. i downplayed it. i didn’t want to make a fuss.
i support all my sisters and my brothers who have been harmed.  don’t let the oppressors silence you and make you afraid.

i was raped when i was 15 years old. i went on a date and got really drunk and high and told him no. it happened anyhow. i repeatedly said no. at the time i didn’t think that it was rape. everything i had seen in the media and such always porayed it as something violent. he didn’t hu me
column2: but he didn’t listen to me either.
i told my friend the story and she said
column3: “he raped you!” i still didn’t think it was in fact rape.

column1: the way we’re force fed a belief system. how were told to think and act. i also never thought it could happen to guys. i was young and naive and misinformed.
i remember the guy was worried that somehow my mom would find out and press charges.
i didn’t tell my mother until i was about 22 or so. i just remember her sighing and saying “well
column2: i’m sorry that happened to you.” and that was that.

column1: at 15 i was out but we didn’t discuss it. i was the rainbow elephant in the room.
i didn’t want to deal with my family and my sexuality. i even less wanted to deal with the fact that i was raped. since i was out in school i felt a magnifying glass was already on me.

column2: because i was scared. i stayed silent because i didn’t fully grasp what had happened to me. because i was confused about what was rape

column1: i still haven’t completely dealt with this past. it feels a million miles away. another lifetime. another me.
but that doesn’t diminish the fact that it happened.
never doubt anyone’s truth. never say that they were asking for it. believe them. comfo them. listen to their stories.
do not let fear take hold. be brave and tell your truths. don’t be made to feel like you’re the villain.
for too long i misconstrued what had happened to be. i downplayed it. i didn’t want to make a fuss.
i suppo all my sisters and my brothers who have been harmed.  don’t let the oppressors silence you and make you afraid.

column1: 337333;instagram;2018-09-29 21:32:19;FALSE;"p r o c e s s i n g & p r a y i n g | this week has been overwhelming and painful to say the least. to look out at humanity and realize that we refuse to see beauty in each other is beyond terrifying. .
conversations about sexual assault and misconduct don’t start or end here. we have to be proactive. #metoo is a call to action
column2: it’s a call to start rethinking our policies in all spaces. starting with the church. it’s possible to create spaces that foster healthy relationships and allow growth. but
column3: in order to do this we have to acknowledge our truth
column5: and allow healing and reconciliation to begin. nothing is healed if it’s hidden.

column1: #silenceisnotspiritual is a beautiful movement that is encouraging churches to pause and look at their own structures and ways that we could create an environment that protects all people and that is truly representative of the population.

i’m still praying and processing and truly taking a time out from all media to see what’s a sustainable solution to a gut wrenching issue that affects us all. efficacy is possible but we have to be willing to take the time and be honest with where we are. .
to know more about the #silenceisnotspiritual movement listen to the @truthstable podcast episode titled by the same name and follow @lisasharper";;en;#metoo

column1: 337348;instagram;2018-09-29 21:47:41;FALSE;"i didn't report in 2012 because i had invited him over. i didnt report because i didn't want to relive the trauma. i didn't report because i didn't have words for what happened. i didn't report because i knew the authorities were more likely to believe him than me.

i didn't report in 2013 because i had been drinking. i didn't report because he was a senior guide and i was a rookie. i didn't report because everybody liked him. i didn't report because we had mutual friends. i didn't report because i didn't trust the management of my company to stand by me.

i didn't report in 2014 because i had to work with him. i didn't report because i was scared of him. i didn't report because the lock on my car door had protected me. i didn't report because i didn't know who to tell. .
i didn't report because in our society it is safer not to. and that needs to change.

column2: still not great 🙃 but i felt the need to add some context in light of the current political climate surrounding the kavanaugh ford hearing. with the rise of the #metoo movement i’ve been inspired to begin a series exploring the effects of not only sexual assault but of rape culture as a whole
column3: filtered through the lens of my personal experiences. i wanted to begin with an uplifting piece
column4: tapping into the wave of female support and rising power and determination “mother (rise).” depicts a personification of the face of the female energy of the earth tilted up
column6: elongated lashes stretching in the direction of her gaze. she is looking beyond the viewer
column7: her gilded eyes completely filled assigning an almost divine importance to her perspective. two sprigs of queen anne’s lace curve into the shape of a halo around her head
column8: a symbol of the sanctity of her vision. a trinity of honey bees buzz about the halo
column9: bringing their reminder of the delicate balance of life on earth. the symmetrical gold tinted glass ferns distort the image beneath them while also bursting out beyond the confines of the hoop creating the sense of an irrepressible energy.

column1: 337383;instagram;2018-09-29 22:06:28;FALSE;"our current political climate & media coverage brings back traumatic memories from high school.
but it also makes me feel extremely blessed to have found my life partner in sean.

we started dating when i was 18 and was fresh out of a traumatic relationship. i had chosen a college 8 hours from home as a last ditch effort to rid myself of a toxic boyfriend. in the two years i dated my ex
column2: i got used to being manipulated

column1: when i would build my courage to confront him and/or try to leave
column2: it would lead to extremely manipulative & exaggerated emotional responses. he’d put his hands on me
column3: throw things and/or threaten suicide. as a teenager
column4: i was too afraid to walk away
column6: and too young to put myself first.

column1: i ran as far as instate tuition would allow and found myself in the mountains of east tn.
it was here that a sweet rugby player found me practicing alone one night & invited me out with his team. it was here that that same sweet guy drove me crazy taking forever to declare his interests
sean & i have since joked about his “shyness” or “reluctance” to make the first move. but when i look back
column2: he did things exactly as he should. i was younger
column4: & emotionally fragile. he treated me with such wisdom by giving me space to make my own decisions & never pressuring me into anything i wasn’t ready for or wanting. what i thought was shyness was actually respect
column5: only my past had left me too battered to know any better.

column1: in our digital age kids mustn’t learn their norms from random blackholes on the internet.
we are over inundated with images of sex but never teach kids about their own need for healthy sexuality.
we must have the awkward conversations and we must monitor children’s digital footprints.
children are capable of predatory behavior that has lasting consequences for their victims & themselves.
all kids deserve the space & time to develop into healthy adults

column1: i ran as far as instate tuition would allow and found myself in the mountains of east tn.

sean & i have since joked about his “shyness” or “reluctance” to make the first move. but when i look back
column2: he did things exactly as he should. i was younger
column4: & emotionally fragile. he treated me with such wisdom by giving me space to make my own decisions & never pressuring me into anything i wasn’t ready for or wanting. what i thought was shyness was actually respect
column5: only my past had left me too battered to know any better.

column1: but i will tell you about one of the most impactful experiences i had with sexual assault

column1: i was 14. i was a cheerleader. an innocent
column3: scared little girl. i only tried out because a friend asked me to go with her. it seemed like fun
column4: but i never thought i would make it.

column2: we were required to wear our uniforms to school on game day. it was busy in our very over crowded high school. i was slammed against my open locker
column3: and felt someone’s hand go up the edge of my briefs under my skirt. i kicked him
column5: and fought my way around and slapped him across the face. he backed up dramatically as if i had stabbed him. i yelled something to the effect of “don’t you ever fucking touch me again” i was sent to the office for my language. i thought “good i will tell them the truth and he’ll get in trouble.” i was naive. i told them the truth. i tried to. they said the halls are crowded and maybe it was an accident. i was told i could file a further complaint
column6: but they would likely have to remove me from the cheerleading squad
column7: and they would have to notify my parents. neither of those were things i had any desire to deal with. so i took my  second option. i went to a single class period of in school suspension for fighting. with the boy who attacked me.

column1: the overwhelming message that hits me while i am sitting here on the porch rocking chair amidst the beautiful nature

column12: so that we can show others it can be moved. .

column1: 337421;instagram;2018-09-29 22:30:17;FALSE;"this is a picture of a vandalized article of my friend @karenavirginia. karena is a kundalini yoga instructor from my home state of nj.  she is also one of the brave women that came forward and accused @realdonaldtrump of harassment before the election. as you can imagine
column2: when she went public her life flipped upside down and the hate she and her family experienced was utterly traumatic. today she posted this picture on instagram with commentary
column5: she was forced to take it down to protect herself and family. in her post she said “i’m done holding secrets society wants held. look what happened to me when i revealed sexual assault on ‘pussy grabber’...i was threatened to death. daily. the death threats were beyond frightening. the lack of support was heartbreaking. how are we contributing to teenagers speaking up when we are afraid to reveal the truth about gurus
column7: spiritual teachers and our communities when they would rather keep secrets secret? how? we aren’t? that is why we are kicking and screaming today...”. with her permission i am posting her pic and a part of her commentary. i stand with karena and all the women who refuse to be silenced. this is not a time for passivity; for waiting for the storm to blow over. we are the storm and we’re not dissipating anytime soon. please show your support for karena by leaving her a message here or on her page. i want her to know that there is support here in the yoga community
column8: and that she is not alone in her efforts and that her voice is welcomed
column9: her experience believed and her spirit valued. #webelieveyou #metoo #whyididntreport #endviolenceagainstwomen #offthematintotheworld @offthemat #silentnomore";;en;#webelieveyou

one might say we have made progress...
and yet we still find ourselves
into a system run and created
by the very hands that mark our bodies
the very eyes that turn us into stone
and the very mouths who can only utter “not i”
and we are labeled the witches
the blamed. damned if we do and damned if we don’t. drunk or not. reported or not. conscious or not.
we are blamed for ruining the lives of men who ruined ours the moment that they took ownership of our bodies
like pirates they invade and name themselves the captain of our own ship
column2: our vessel. they come aboard and leave our ships cracked
column3: holes being filled up by an ocean of tears never to be mopped up. and as we stand
column4: broken captains of a broken ship
column5: we begin to blame ourselves and sometimes - we sink with our own ship. often
column6: it takes years and years of searching and fighting that same fight. the fight to once again take ownership of our bodies
column8: and once again rise above sea level and set course for a new journey

column1: i attended one of the most amazing events last weekend. at the @drivenevent organized by the power couple @thealbertpreciado and @sylpreciado . we were challenged by one of the amazing speakers (which included @elenacardone @tailopez @therealbradlea @patrickbetdavid)  to reflect on one of the simplest but most important questions we can ask ourselves moving forward from any event and honestly stepping into every day. …
who do you want to be?
this morning i asked myself that question and sat in a presence of ease
column3: a presence of rest and femininity and flow.

column1: and then i took this picture.
this is me feeling incredibly beautiful and radiant.
👑 i love the way my frizzy and life-filled hair declared its presence with no product in it to “tame my curls.”

👑i love the way my hair parted natural slightly off center. sitting where it felt most present and comfortable. 👑i love the way my eyebrows boldly did their thing without being shaped and penciled in.
👑i love the way my face radiated
column2: as its going through an amazing season of healing
column3: the scars and spots on my chin and cheeks being a beautiful representation of that. 👑i love the way my face seemed to breathe and radiate with no makeup

column1: loving how i felt in the world today. i realized that the way i feel today is who i want to be tomorrow. and the next day. and the next.
i want to be a woman that sits in her beauty
column5: her capacity for a depth of love and compassion that is able to breathe life into her own children
column6: beings made of her and by her
column7: and to breathe life into the world in a time when we need it more and more with each passing day. #metoo

column1: i want to be the woman that wakes up every morning listening to her heart and soul daily upon waking. the person that pursues that inner guidance wholeheartedly. the person that spends time with her spirit guides
column5: with mother earth daily and listens to their gentle whispers always.

column1: 337453;instagram;2018-09-29 22:50:47;FALSE;"**content warning: discussion of gendered violence and power** i keep thinking about my roommate just crying because we had a quiet moment together to finally feel everything. and about my mom who said she caught a glimpse of her reflection yesterday and noticed her cheeks were flushed because she has just been enraged for days.
i've been in the presence of some people in the last few days who are both deeply sad and absolutely powerful. thank you for expressing yourselves so sincerely and sharing space and pain.
none of those people were men. no men past or present that i've been close friends with or had a relationship with have checked in to see how i am
column3: or ask about the power dynamics between us (past or present.) i'm noticing. you should too.

column1: 337455;instagram;2018-09-29 22:52:16;TRUE;;"proud of my 17-year old daughter @bronwenbrenner who — along with a group of  thoughtful
column2: articulate young people —shared her thoughts about brett kavanaugh with teen vogue. #repost @bronwenbrenner with @get_repost

column1: i wrote this over a week ago and have been going back and forth about sharing.
if there was ever a time for sharing my story
column2: it feels like it’s now. it’s been years. and i’ve written it out in my head over and over and over
column3: and said it out loud even fewer times. i let the #metoo movement blow up without sharing
column4: i’ve sat and listened to so many other stories
column5: and it’s never felt like the time to share. but with kavanaugh
column6: it has felt like a zillion little sparkers going off in my brain
column7: telling me that now is the time to say it out loud.

column1: kavanaugh is one of millions. the cockroaches of this country who think they can get away with anything. i hate him
column2: and as i listen to christine blasey ford’s graphic description my mind plays over and over and over the scene when i was 17. when i was at a small party
column4: and raped by someone that i thought i knew well. by someone who went to an all boys christian high school- just like kavanaugh. the lines between coercion and forcible rape were incredibly blurry. i knew what happened was wrong
column7: but it took until college until really putting words to it. it took learning consent to understand that what happened to me was the opposite. it took nearly 5 years to say it out loud
column9: i have said it just a few times- and i really do remember it like it was yesterday
column10: as i know christine blasey ford does as well. that’s what trauma does
column11: it imprints in your mind and is louder than a usual memory- replaying at different volumes
column12: never giving you the option of when it comes up.

column1: but the experience and awareness i can share is that  i’ve too been scared of men. on the street. in my car. even just last week i had to get off the freeway to ditch someone who was driving erratically to stay near me and be able to look at me in his mirrors or by driving right next to me

column1: 337483;instagram;2018-09-29 23:14:06;FALSE;"i have been starting to curl into myself the past few days. i have been listening to the friends i love tell their stories. it’s astounding that there are so many of us carrying around this pain. it’s been a viscous cycle of shame
column5: & screaming for me. i know i’m not alone but that doesn’t make it okay. i wish no one had to suffer. i wish we were all respectful of boundaries. i wish we were supported when we were brave enough to tell our stories. i wish so many fucking things...

column1: i am so very thankful for finally finding healthy coping skills. i used to try to numb it all away. i am thankful to be in a band that lets me express my pain in other ways. this song played on my way home and i had the hugest smile on my face. i know i heal a little more every time i get to sing it out loud. i love my band mates and appreciate everyone who has supported us on our journey.
sending love and healing to all in need.✨💚✨

column1: 337502;instagram;2018-09-29 23:19:42;FALSE;"""difficult"" doesn't even begin to describe the past week for many of us - including myself. i know i'm not the only one feeling drained and triggered. i have found myself wanting to respond in a post
column2: but deleting my words time and time again...

column1: you are not required to share your story just because this topic is trending. just as you didn't owe anything to the person who assaulted you
column2: you don't owe anything to any of us. what i want you to know is that you are not alone. you are not any less than. you did not deserve what happened to you - no one deserves to be violated. you may not feel strong and resilient

column1: if you are a friend or loved one of a survivor -
thank you. thank you for listening
column2: believing and supporting us. thank you for your patience as we navigate healing. thank you for being angry with us and for us. thank you for asking if you can touch us for a hug. thank you for respecting our privacy. thank you for just being there. your love and support mean more to us than you know.

column1: to those of you who question or criticize survivors for reporting

i hope you found the time to watch dr. ford's testimony to the senate judiciary committee. i hope you managed to grasp the courage and bravery it took for her to detail her sexual assault in front of an entire nation only to have her integrity and character questioned over and over again (while keeping her composure). she stood-up for herself and all survivors - that is an incredibly heavy burden to bear. i hope you didn't just listen to her words
trauma doesn't go away. you can work through it and try to find tools to manage it
column2: but trauma stays with you - and can be triggered unexpectedly. it shouldn't take a trending topic for us to believe survivors and hold abusers accountable.

column1: you know those days...maybe even weeks that just weigh you down? ones where despite your best efforts to stay grateful and hopeful
column2: you feel extra heavy? maybe a little blue? .

column1: today has been one of those days. personal struggles. memories and heartbreak for those lost. exhaustion in my existence as a woman in this country’s current reality. .
wanting to say anything of substance...anything that might help things make sense. to myself and others around me.  feeling helpless and overwhelmed at the thought of where to start. .
all that muck brought me to my mat today. solid 40 minute practice after quite a long hiatus. hijacked a playlist from @fitqueenirene and let the movement evolve. .
inevitably my mind races during my flow
column2: yet i still found some quiet...even if only for a second. thoughts on how to support @samseesworld and @bodhimovement with trying to do as much good as possible. thoughts on unexpected circumstances i now need to navigate through. thoughts on how i can make more of an impact. and then one more thought about how exhausted i am. .

column2: age 28 (suicidal ideation): it’s a hot topic right now but harassment and assault are unfortunately a staple part of the female experience and right now at the forefront of women vs men relations. i’d like to call attention though to other types of #metoo involving same sex harassment and assault of both men and women that rarely gets into the spotlight. it’s degrading
column3: it’s silent and it carries an even greater stigma upon confession. it also has a lot of enablers because of that stigma and gets put under the rug under the guise of “hazing” or “mean girls” or “being rough.” i’m not going to get into my own specifics except to say it really affected me when i didn’t get assistance from those who could help as i consider that too personal for the internet but i’d like to put out there for #suicideprevention ‘s sake that the #lgbtq community has a much higher incidence in this area for both males and females and where you have assault and harassment you have a high increase in suicide risk. make sure you check on your friends

column1: @regran_ed from @seanecorn -  this is a picture of a vandalized article of my friend @karenavirginia. karena is a kundalini yoga instructor from my home state of nj.  she is also one of the brave women that came forward and accused @realdonaldtrump of harassment before the election. as you can imagine
column2: when she went public her life flipped upside down and the hate she and her family experienced was utterly traumatic. today she posted this picture on instagram with commentary
column5: she was forced to take it down to protect herself and family. in her post she said “i’m done holding secrets society wants held. look what happened to me when i revealed sexual assault on ‘pussy grabber’...i was threatened to death. daily. the death threats were beyond frightening. the lack of support was heartbreaking. how are we contributing to teenagers speaking up when we are afraid to reveal the truth about gurus
column7: spiritual teachers and our communities when they would rather keep secrets secret? how? we aren’t? that is why we are kicking and screaming today...”. with her permission i am posting her pic and a part of her commentary. i stand with karena and all the women who refuse to be silenced. this is not a time for passivity; for waiting for the storm to blow over. we are the storm and we’re not dissipating anytime soon. please show your support for karena by leaving her a message here or on her page. i want her to know that there is support here in the yoga community

column1: 337560;instagram;2018-09-29 23:56:08;FALSE;relationship violence is something that unfortunately happens to so many women
column2: it’s hard to gauge an accurate number. my personal experience with relationship violence began at the age of 13. i didn’t realize the boy i was dating was angry at me for some reason
column3: and when i went to sit on his lap he pushed me so hard i skidded across the floor in the middle of a room full of people. my friends were so stunned it took days for them to come to me and tell me they thought i should break up with him. i was so young
column4: i thought it was my fault. years later
column5: i found myself in a toxic relationship with a boy/man (we dated from ages 18-21) who would take the information i gave him about the abuse i had already endured
column7: and use it against me. for instance- (trigger warning: violence) one night he got me drunk on pinot grigio and asked me extremely personal questions about my father’s sexual abuse in front of his mom. when i had been reduced to tears
column8: he took me downstairs and threw me on the floor and ripped my shirt and bra in half while he straddled me from above. i was so drunk
column11: and enraged by this that i fought back
column12: and hard. i just remember beating my head against his head while he held my arms down and i struggled against him until i saw stars. i ended up giving myself a concussion. i tell you this story for a reason
column13: even though it’s hard to recount: your reaction to abuse is not your fault
column14: and it doesn’t make you a bad person. when someone is abusing and taking advantage of you
column15: your fight or flight instincts kick in and it literally may feel like life or death in the worst moments. it’s not your fault. if you hurt them back
column16: it’s time to leave. never feel bad for leaving an abusive or toxic situation. if someone tells you they’ll hurt you or themselves if you leave them- get out as soon as you can and never look back. stay safe

column1: 337583;instagram;2018-09-30 00:12:47;FALSE;"- speak your truth whenever you feel like speaking your truth!  there is no time limit on when you can say something.  if something happened to you 25 years ago
column2: and today you feel like saying what happened... then good for you! stand strongly in your truth
column3: regardless of who believes you.  many people say that “nothing could have happened to somebody if they are just now bringing it up.” just because it happened a long time ago does not change the fact that it did happen!  just because one chooses to tell their story when they feel ready to tell it does not change the fact that their story is true. fuck your timeframes and fuck your victim-blaming bullshit!!! if the individuals being accused of something don’t like being accused ...then they should not have done what they did! - what is done in the dark always comes to light.

column1: i am really just getting tired of talking about the current events because it’s so triggering and frustrating and the way that many people are talking about it even more infuriating. i believe in righteous anger
column2: and i believe that righteous anger is what is going to change this world. yet
column3: lately i just want to focus on love
column5: self care and hope. that’s just me though. everyone is allowed to react differently. do you. our existence alone is a resistance. 👏🏼

column1: 337593;instagram;2018-09-30 00:16:57;FALSE;"i’m a day late but here’s my weekly blog as promised 🌸 ‘in light of the conversations infecting our on and offline lives as #billcosby & #kavanaugh make headlines and we continue to find reasons not to #muterkelly
column2: i felt like this was an appropriate #throwback for the blog.
you deserve every good thing and the basic level of decency you have yet to receive from society is- at the very least- shared among us.

column1: this is the first time i’ve declared #metoo or #believesurvivors since these particular men began to make waves (again)
column2: not because i don’t care or because i haven’t been paying attention- but because black women never receive the level of support
column4: empathy or goodwill that we as a society show other demographics of women.

column1: the conversation explored in this particular blog is an in house one.
but we would all do well to reflect on who has been shouting into the void to no avail
column2: whose movements lose sight of their very creators when they go mainstream (shout out to @taranajaneen)
column4: the names we forget and who we choose to publicly uplift in a world where we could educate ourselves at the push of a button and restructure our organizing and ‘allyship’ accordingly.

column1: shout out to anita hill & kimberlè crenshaw.’ from the article: ‘i kept seeing the word ‘realistic’ used in reference to her comments. as if raising boys who are not rapists was some kind of unattainable goal and the best we could do is police the attire of our women and girls in the hopes young men can keep their composure.
in any scenario when a man of any age is given the option of blaming predatory behavior on nature and not his own lack of self control we are not being ‘realistic.’ we are making excuses.

column3: suggest that male sexuality is stronger than male self control- and provide a narrative that suggests the onus of responsibility is on women not to be raped
column4: instead of on men not to commit rape
column5: we are failing an entire community.

column1: 337625;instagram;2018-09-30 00:34:53;FALSE;"i'm proud of all the women who have come forward. i stand with you all. i used to blame myself. but no more.
1. he worked with me at mcdonald's. i was 15. he felt like a friend. then he started groping me whenever he'd walk past. he was twice my age.
2. he was the 40 year old son of my manager. he hid a picture of his genitals amongst pictures of his newborn baby on his phone
column2: just so i'd ""stumble upon it"" as i looked through the images of his new child. his friends and my manager were around when it happened and they laughed at this ""joke."" _________________________________

column1: 3. he was a cop. a literal cop. when things got inappropriate
column3: since it's 'his people' that i would have to go to. ________________________________________________

column1: 4. he was drunk. we were at a get-together. when i went to use the restroom
column2: he pushed me into the bedroom off to the side
column4: and began kissing me. i had to literally push him off and run away. ________________________________________________

column1: 5. he was married to one of my friends
column2: and he'd sneakily tell me that ""one of these days he'll have his way with me."" we were in a location where his wife and friends took the stairs
column3: and i had to take an elevator. he joined me in the elevator. when i went silent and got noticeably scared
column5: i'm not going to try anything with you... yet."" _________________________________

column1: 6. he was a classmate who i studied with one time. he began calculating out how many times he's had sex on the board and telling me how strong he is. he told me he was a black belt
column2: who always wore sweatpants just in case ""he ever got attacked
column3: or if he needed to be agile he could dominate the opposite person."" he made it clear i was an intended ""opposite person."" _______________________________________

column1: 7. he was a friend who drove me home on a weird route
column2: which led to a random field where he parked and turned off the car. he held me down
column4: and i kept asking him to stop. i had to push him away multiple times before he got mad and drove me home.

column1: do not make excuses for someone's poor actions. what they did was wrong.

column1: i have a great deal to be thankful for this year. for the good bad and ugly i saw in other people and in myself for that matter.

3 years ago i was at the trailer and my mind was on fire with a desire for something wild and crazy. a wellness centre. a safe place. a community. a store and studio. a place for education. a place where someone was passionate about women’s health.

column2: my insatiable urge to perceiver and my stubborn attitude to get shit done. i had a village of people who were excited about my abilities and even more who were reluctant- which was more driving force.

column1: i had my severance from the military (fee bucks in my pocket) and the sheer tenacity in my soul for an adventure like this. .
i’ve grown and faltered. i’ve flourished and closed doors for mental health. i’ve succeeded professionally and failed personally. but i haven’t given up. on occasion i had doubts
when i honed in on exactly what i wanted to help women with in the community
column3: i was able to release all the outside noise and focus on a few set priorities.

column1: hormonal/reproductive/sexual health. it is imperative women past present and future are heard and assisted. our knowledge should be limitless for our own health
column2: and i wanted to be apart of that experience. i needed healing because the magnitude of #metoo runs deep in my bones since childhood and never stopped. i needed healing because the lack of gnosis that unfortunately wasn’t passed down to me hindered my way of life and my connection to my body.
myths and fear. and at the end of the day
column3: if i needed all of this
column4: chances were so did other women. .

column1: with my desire to help others and keep my busy mind at bay
column2: her wellness opened a few short months after this thought. this december will be 3yrs open
column3: but this month was my muse. my spark was lit and my flame was bright. .

column1: thank you to all who have and continue to share in the growth and support of her wellness. to all those who don’t. with kindness
column2: kiss my humble ass. i am here to stay. her health is worth it 💗 #truth #words #entrepreneur #womenshealth";;en;#metoo

column1: 337639;instagram;2018-09-30 00:40:30;FALSE;"the current news cycle has been rough
column2: and the heaviness has been setting in more the last couple days. many of us who have dealt with sexual assault are forced to replay our own stories in our heads
column3: reliving painful memories and experiences. wondering how we would be treated if we chose to speak about things we haven't yet. remembering why we either didn't report
column4: or remembering why it was so hard to report at all. thinking about all the ways we could be blamed for what happened to us
column5: and how it could be portrayed as our fault. forever doubting ourselves and downplaying things that have happened. always feeling like we'd just be seen as a ""whiny female"" if we spoke up. it's heavy and it's painful.•

column1: but more than anything i am angered at the 'normalcy' of assault stories. i am angry that my best friend and i can easily share story upon story of sexual harassment and assaults and we haven't even touched the tip of the iceberg. i am angry that i have experienced sexual assault on varying levels more than three times in my life and that i question myself and i downplay it and don't talk about it because years later i still feel like it was my fault. i question myself. i was told it could have been worse. i was told i shouldn't have put myself in a situation. i was asked what i was wearing. i was asked if i led them on. it is always implied that me and other females must have in some way asked for it. so why would we talk about it? •

i am just tired and i am sad. i pray hard for everyone who has also been emotionally and mentally effected by the news stories lately. it doesn't matter where you stand on the stories and the issues. if you've been a victim

column1: how many ways as a woman do you prepare yourself and brace yourself each day? how many ways have you told your daughters
column4: etc tips on how to protect yourself/themselves? how do you think about how you dress? what route you'll take? do you grip your keys in your fist? or have a stungun or mace in your hand?

column2: when something does happen i mean...you were kinda expecting it
column4: that's why you prepared yourself each day.

column2: what? was it just a scare? you weren't completely violated so is it something you just tell a loved one about? you take even more steps to insulate yourself each day? do you hide in your house or behind baggy clothes?

column1: or maybe it was worse so...you go to the police? you go through the questioning? the rape kit with strangers in the room
column2: touching you where you were already violated? more questioning? you go home feeling striped away and completely alone and naked in the middle of the day behind locked doors? and you wait for the authorities to...help.

column1: or you don't tell anyone. you shower
column5: you keep doing your daily life. you shove it down
column6: you hide or you act out. anything to take back some power and control. .

column1: and maybe one day you get the nerve to speak out. and...what? you maybe get a pat on the hand. a sympathetic nod. and then...a question. the question. any of the questions that mean
column2: what did you do to deserve this? it had to have been something...what were you wearing? were you drinking? did you flirt with him? why did you go there didn't you know better? why didn't you tell someone? .

column1: and then. you know. you know you aren't believed. i mean...why would you be. you aren't believed now so why would you be believed then? .

i'll listen. and i'll believe you. because i've been there. i've rocked myself crying & feeling ashamed & dirty & broken. i've also stood in the rape processing exam room. and i've taken your calls in the middle of the night through a rape crisis center. every age
and. i'm sorry. and it's not your fault.

column1: 337661;instagram;2018-09-30 00:55:14;FALSE;"there were a million reasons i loved this shoot of @shineblackhawk but one of them is that she showed me all of her. she didn't hide her darkness. she owned it. women have been told that angry women are ugly women. i have never believed that to be true and in fact
column2: i find that women who have harnessed their anger in a positive way are the most powerful
column4: beautiful women i know. i know that many of you are feeling angry and triggered by this week's news cycle. me too.

column1: i'm angry because i want things to be different for my daughter than they were for me. i'm angry because if this country isn't going to pursue justice for dr. ford who is an educated
column6: than i shudder to think about what that means for women of color who also deserve justice from our judicial system.  i have been paying close attention this week. i have watched how white
column8: who are scared of losing of their power can throw tantrums like children and are praised for it
column9: rewarded even. i have read countless posts by women whose wounds have been ripped open by watching another woman tell her story to a world that seems not to care and in fact blames her for being assaulted. i know that many of you who follow this page are trauma survivors. and i want you to know that my heart is with you. i am allowing myself to be mad and i have also made a conscious decision not to hide my anger. we all have something to learn from kamala harris. she was visibly angry and yet

column1: 337667;instagram;2018-09-30 00:58:02;FALSE;"“life is not easy for any of us. but what of that? we must have perseverance and above all confidence in ourselves. we must believe that we are gifted for something

column3: and i want to pop in here and sneak a little motivation into your weekend.

column1: october is posture month on the yoga infusion channel. that means that every class that comes out will have been designed specifically to work on bettering our posture. now why is that important?

column3: poor posture can lead to health problems and pain as we grow older and it becomes more prominent.
poor posture is a sign of a weak or imbalanced heart and/or throat chakra. it is our way to hunch the shoulders forward
column7: can become permanent. and this folding into ourselves signals to the brain that we need this protection
column8: this armor. it tells our brain that we want to be small

column1: but why hide? why should we be small?
i want to encourage you all today
column6: and tell the world that you are here. that you matter. that you mean something. that you are an amazing individual and you’re not going anywhere. i want you to tell yourself that as well. you matter. you belong here. you are loved.

column1: everyone wants to say ""boys will be boys"" and ""what happened to innocent until proven guilty""
did you have that same energy when zimmerman murdered trayvon?
did you have the same energy when 12 year old tamir rice was playing in a park and murdered?
did you have that same energy when cosby was on trial?
did you have that same energy when all these now men came forward stating they were molested by catholic priests?

column3: but put a white upperclass male in the light for the accusation of crime and all this comes out. you same people defended zimmermans right to ""stand your ground"" you same people stated tamir shouldnt have been playing with anything that resembled a gun (cause gosh forbid a 12 year old boy plays) you stated ""cosby did it
column4: he has to be punished"" (no doubt i agree he needed to be as well)

column1: you stated ""how could those priests do that 30+ years ago
column2: those poor boys"" now you sit and ridicule this woman for finally being brave enough to come forward
column3: not only to her family and closest confidants
column4: but to a nation. you question why she waited 30+ years. you question her motive
column5: you question her memory. you question every aspect of her while excusing male behavior as ""boys will be boys"" as if its a natural thing.

column1: while doing all that you scream loudly how liberals are the problem in the world. how liberals are whats wrong. no
column2: whats wrong is somewhere along the lines a majority of yall lost your compassion
column4: decency and morals. while you sit there stating how youll pray for me cause im so lost and uneducated
column5: please also turn around and pray for yourself
column6: take a long look in the mirror and really really re-think it all. while you make excuses for this assaulter
column7: remember the message you are sending your daughters
column11: and aquaintances. you are letting them know that you are not the person they can every turn too. you are telling them you dont care

unworthy of the truth, of respect and even told that you deserve to be punished just for existing....it wears on you. i am a survivor of sexual, physical, emotional and psychological abuse. in the top photo i’m about 9 or 10. i’ve been drugged to sleep and molested many times at that point. ive seen my mother and my sister hurt in ways no one should ever have to see or hear. i learned to be funny as a way of diffusing the bomb that we all lived with. i learned to be clever in hopes of my abuser seeing me as human. i’ve had suicidal thoughts. i’ve also prayed to and believed in angels. in the bottom photo i am about 26 or 27 and experiencing the peak of self medication to sooth myself into deep slumber. i’ve battled to stay in my body. i’ve lost sometimes. but won the fight for my soul. i’m a living miracle. if you  survived that bullshit you are too. #metoo #ibelieveher #ripthepatriarchy #survivorstories;;en;#metoo, #ibelieveher, #ripthepatriarchy, 337693;instagram;2018-09-30 01:14:14;FALSE;what does it look like when we speak our truth. ?

right now women are witnessing their own stories of sexual assault rising within them. like many people having experienced sexual assault i was triggered by the #metoo movement. i was raped when i was 18 and was supported by the police. the case was dismissed at the hearing for not enough evidence despite my bruised face and scratches in the inside of my thighs from the velcro on his shorts. white men in power  judging me -the qc and judge were pissing in each other’s pockets and i had to answer questions on the stand like ‘did i enjoy it’ whilst looking at the perpetrator who had big shit eating smile on his face. it was dismissed for not enough evidence
column2: despite the fact i could take the police to the place where it happened and we found the money laying on the ground that i had recalled falling out. i praise & honour the brave young girl i was
column3: whilst i acknowledge the wounding which has a tendency to flare up. i am proud of the warrior i was even then. he was a footballer and i was able to use the adrenaline surging through me to push him off me with my legs. i could barely walk the next day  my legs were so sore. even writing this i recall the moment i knew when he was going to rape me - after i tried to talk my way out of it. when i said i might have aids ( in desperation) and he said ‘good so might i’ i filled with dread i tried to move out from under him ( prior he forced me to the ground) and he quickly responded and restrained me from moving like a cat playing with a mouse. i remember tilting my head back to mark out my escape route - i was planning to fight for my survival. and fight i did. he was walking me to safely get a cab and the park was a short cut(  i knew  him through my basketball team). he told the police when he was arrested he thought we were going to do some ‘smutting’ . to all the women who are feeling triggered or vulnerable right now i stand with you. as a doctor who has been sexually assaulted i know some days you feel strong
column4: other days you are not. talk  to people you trust..
