column1: 337712;instagram;2018-09-30 01:30:03;FALSE;as a follow up to my last post
column2: and in response to public and private messages i’ve received: being a victim of sexual assault is hard. even when you don’t really understand the extremity of it (did i really understand the gravity of what happened to me that night a decade ago? no). as for me
column3: i’m fine. although i never spoke publicly about it
column4: i was able to internally make peace with it and move on. it didn’t take hold of me
column5: despite the memory flittering through my mind from time to time. that’s not the case for all victims. many many victims experience ptsd for a lifetime
column7: are unable to forge close bonds with others
column8: put two doors in their home as an extra escape route... it doesn’t manifest in the same way for everyone. i’m most disgusted by the people (mainly women) who lack any sort of empathy to acknowledge the fact that some victims sadly hold this memory close for years and years. healing does not and should not have a time limit. and if you feel you have the chance to right a wrong in this world and feel safe enough to do so
column9: take it. we should not be shamed for speaking up or using our voices. i find it interesting that my post about my rape was so quiet. few “reactions” and comments
column10: yet posts of my dogs and happy photos of me happy with my little family get tons of attention. i know you saw my post. i want to make it clear that it is okay to discuss hard things if the victim is okay with it. there is no reason that we can’t talk about the hard stuff as friends and family. this is how we grow as a society

column3: having this platform flooded with post after post of women rising up and sharing their voice
column4: it was easy to be impacted by the energy.

column1: the libra in me that stands for justice can heavily and intensely be swallowed up by a fiery passion and consumed when i get behind a movement that i believe in.
and i know that this is the energy that these times are needing from me
column4: for those that weren’t listened to. for those that were violated. for those that were made to feel unworthy of their no.

column1: is disgustingly far too common. but the conversation is necessary. this discussion is mandatory. and should no longer be hidden and made to feel shameful and embarrassed of. it’s time to heal. heal so that our future generations know better and do better.
i can’t help but think of my son and the world he is growing in. he is being raised to know compassion and respect for all. to listen
column3: to love unconditionally. i wonder what the world will be like for him as he gets older.. all of the women in me wants to stand up and roar with millions of others!

column1: but i find myself witnessing in awe
column2: of the waves that are being made. of the foundations being destroyed only to build a new. of the courage blanketing this globe.

column1: i can only trust that the work i’ve been called to offer
column2: will continue to be a container
column4: a home for those that seek to unleash their voice after lifetimes of being silenced and made to feel unworthy and not good enough.

column1: this is a picture of a vandalized article of my friend @karenavirginia. karena is a kundalini yoga instructor from my home state of nj.  she is also one of the brave women that came forward and accused @realdonaldtrump of harassment before the election. as you can imagine
column2: when she went public her life flipped upside down and the hate she and her family experienced was utterly traumatic. today she posted this picture on instagram with commentary
column5: she was forced to take it down to protect herself and family. in her post she said “i’m done holding secrets society wants held. look what happened to me when i revealed sexual assault on ‘pussy grabber’...i was threatened to death. daily. the death threats were beyond frightening. the lack of support was heartbreaking. how are we contributing to teenagers speaking up when we are afraid to reveal the truth about gurus
column7: spiritual teachers and our communities when they would rather keep secrets secret? how? we aren’t? that is why we are kicking and screaming today...”. with her permission i am posting her pic and a part of her commentary. i stand with karena and all the women who refuse to be silenced. this is not a time for passivity; for waiting for the storm to blow over. we are the storm and we’re not dissipating anytime soon. please show your support for karena by leaving her a message here or on her page. i want her to know that there is support here in the yoga community
column8: and that she is not alone in her efforts and that her voice is welcomed
column9: her experience believed and her spirit valued. #webelieveyou #metoo #whyididntreport #endviolenceagainstwomen #offthematintotheworld @offthemat #silentnomore";en;#Repost

column3: the last two years have been..... a shitshow is really the only term i can think of to describe it. ⠀⠀

column1: i’ve gone from reading the news daily to briefly skimming and occasionally going in depth once a week while receiving most of the shitshow summary from my husband. i had to do this for my mental and emotional well being. ⠀⠀
i’m fucking tired. tired of the bullshit. i wish i could say i was horrified by the actions of the men in power that unquestionably let women know that we don’t matter to them
column2: but it’s more a sense of relief that they’re not hiding it anymore. relief because the fight has now gone so public that my beautifully woman-centric/truth in beauty
column3: plant spirit medicine curated instagram feed is now 98% posts that make me think
column5: make me feel strong in our solidarity even more then they already did. and there is no more denying it. ⠀⠀

column1: i see amazing men around me waking up to the truths women experience daily and being outraged by this reality.  @serpentfire so eloquently put it ~ “even if we ourselves have not been a victim of violence or sexual violence the very real possibility that we could be keeps us hyper vigilant. in this society
column4: the gauging “can i run in these shoes?… if i’m being followed
column5: what are my plans of action?… etc...”

column1: dr. christine blasey ford deserves a goddamn medal for coming forward
column3: for living with this experience that is dismissed by rape culture. but since we are not yet at the time where we celebrate strong women unequivocally perhaps we might send her a note of thanks for being a warrior. address in second pic. ⠀⠀

column3: and two columns in-antis at the entrance behind the colonnade.

column1: 337782;instagram;2018-09-30 02:24:01;FALSE;i’m sick of a common theme around the conversations about sexual assault/ abuse & rape that i see daily. a lack of understanding
column2: sympathy & empathy along with so many misconceptions. before you don’t read any further or dismiss what i have to say
column3: i too was sexually abused as a child. this is not public knowledge to most people i know. but the conversations need to change along with understanding. i guarantee many people in your life are also affected by this but can’t speak about it nor do i expect everyone too. we primarily think of the victims as female which is a majority but don’t underestimate the amount of males affected also. just because something happened 20 years ago doesn’t mean that it’s either “made up” or “in the past so get over it”. unless this has happened to you
column4: you will never understand the impact at the time and the impact on your daily life forever. often confronting the abuser or public acknowledgement would do more damage than good. so you often are left with suppressing it until you can’t no more. every conversation on this topic in the news
column8: social media you name it is a daily reminder of the past. when i was younger it was easier to suppress it
column9: but as i get older it’s a struggle almost daily especially given the recent supreme court talks
column10: it’s everywhere. i don’t want this to be about one story. this is bigger than that. but what kills me is the conversations i see from people who don’t nor ever will understand
column11: you do not understand the harsh and damaging conversations you are having. i beg of you to give people the benefit of the doubt first
column12: try to exercise empathy and be willing to open your mind to what you don’t know or understand. i do not want this to be about me

column1: 337795;instagram;2018-09-30 02:39:22;FALSE;"i’m seeing a lot of division surrounding #believewomen

as with it’s equally important predecessor #blacklivesmatter people are loosing their effing minds over the absolutism of this language. i want to take a moment to tell you all what this statement does and does not mean to me.
it doesn’t mean everything coming out of a woman’s mouth is to be believed
column2: it does mean that our truths and experiences are almost always ignored and deemed unimportant particularly when we speak out about sexual assault.

column1: in order to face this patriarchal precedent we have to distill our pain and anger into something digestible. we have to scream something from the rooftops and since #pleasecarethatwomenarebeingassualtedmolestedandraped isn’t especially catchy we have created something a little easier to type. believe women is a slogan
column2: intended to insight a fraction of empathy and awareness from a society that tells us our pain is imagined. our experiences are unimportant. we are hysterical. we are lying money grubbing bitches hell bent on celebrity at the expense of innocent men.

column1: remember for a moment that we live in an era of slogans
column4: idea or change to gain traction it must be accompanied by a memorable quip.

column2: you probably should just believe women making accusations of sexual abuse because studies have show that a staggeringly low 2-8% of woman making accusations are lying.

column2: it does mean that our truths and experiences are almost always ignored and deemed unimportant particularly when we speak out about sexual assault.

column2: he had to point out to me that i was a survivor. -

column1: my first serious boyfriend begged for physical intimacy that i was not ready for. a metamour took things to a place in a sexual situation
column2: that was never discussed to gain my consent beforehand. there is more i do not wish to share at this point. -

column1: when other people have confided situations like this to me i have validated them. i said yes this is sexual assault
column3: and no it is not your fault. -

column1: those experiences have been twisting around in my guts for all the years i was trying to figure out why physical intimacy frightened me. it has taken me years to give myself the space to acknowledge that i had experienced sexual assault. my wounds are finally able to breath. i am finally giving space in my body to feel it. i refuse to let someone learn from my past examples of gagging yourself for the love of another. so yes

column3: of us have experienced sexual assault and harassment at least once in our lives. i stand in solidarity with every woman and child  who has endured sexual torment. after reading so many stories #metoo #whyididntreport it began to feel like every woman has been a victim and every man has been a perpetrator. i realize that that’s simply not the case. i grew up in a very specific violent era and region. los angeles was the murder capital of the country when i was a teenager. we were living “boyz in da hood” and “menace to society”. the world didn’t think much of my peer group. but looking back on my youth
column4: i can remember many times that i may have been “asking for it” or put myself in “a bad position” but the teenaged boys and young men heard my no and respected it. this post is for them. #notyou #boyznthehood #bloods #crips #superpredators #crackepidemic #1990 #southcentral #losangeles #blacklivesmatter #blackboy #gangster #gangsta #blacklove #blackteenagers #teenagedboys #cancelkavanaugh #believewomen #ibelieveher #ibelievechristineblaseyford #feminist #blackfeminist #womanist #womanism #lawyermom #girlmom #workingmom;;en;#metoo

column1: 337828;instagram;2018-09-30 03:02:12;FALSE;"✨you guys...😭 for those of you who know my story
column2: know that i grew up in an environment where i had to grow up far too fast. although i never wanted to be the child who learned people could take advantage of me
column3: the girl who had to scream to get her father to stop beating her siblings
column4: or the kid who would had to lie about her mother’s hoarding addiction... it happened.

column1: in all of this my few good memories were with people outside of my parents.
but somehow when we grow older
column2: even those good things are overwhelmed by the work and traumas (in my case ptsd) that bury those things alive.

column1: i had become “mr. banks” in so many ways... i’m so thankful for the many reminders this week of wonder (and i got to meet my favorite princess!!)🐠. if you’ve read my blog about “inner child theory” you will also know that this has been part of my healing process. this past week my inner 8yr old definitely came out! but this time she wasn’t afraid. she saw magic and learned laughter. and the grown me was not afraid to let her be free.✨ i’m still healing. so can you🖤

column1: i believe he’s guilty... based largely because i do not believe a woman is going to step forward and accuse him of attempted rape from thirty something years ago when doing so pushes her into the media spotlight worldwide. that’s a terrifying prospect for anyone. to potentially be viewed as a liar
column3: with suspicion and even downright ridicule. women are raped and experience attempted rape all the time and don’t dare tell anyone. so often we’re afraid that no one will believe us. or we will be blamed. i was raped at 17. i stand beside blasey ford and her statements. i see her for her courage and great bravery. i see that brett kavanaugh is an angry man who is lashing out
column4: talking about how much he loves beer 🍻 and sarcastically redirecting the questions he was asked by democrats back on them. i see him as a man who feels angry he was caught and very little to no empathy for his accuser. i see him coming unglued due to the old ways of the world no longer working for him because women are killing the male entitlement of patriarchy and replacing it with truth and accountability through the me too movement. i noticed not one republican asked him a single question regarding blasey ford and the details of the attempted rape. instead they all massaged his ego and wiped his rear for him with compliments... i’ve been a republican all my life. but i can say i was horrified by the republicans reaction to this situation. i’m anxious to see the results of the investigation.... we need the truth. regardless the good ole boys have been in charge too long... and we as women aren’t willing to take their bs any longer. my hope is the old ways are dying and being replaced with the way of women. 🙌🏼

column1: 337849;instagram;2018-09-30 03:20:22;FALSE;"this week has been a heavy week personally and for people around the world with certain events happening on the television. it hurts me to see so many people in pain. it also hurts to see so much anger in the world.

column2: understand your feelings and then let them go. holding onto the hurt and anger will just make you suffer more
column3: not them. don't let them take anything else away from you
column4: they don't deserve another minute of your precious time. don't let one situation poison your beautiful soul
column5: or let one imperfect human being keep you from what you know is true and right because they don't know how to handle a situation or problem you have
column6: anchor your soul to light and love.

column3: you are worthy of all the goodness life offers you!

column1: 337984;instagram;2018-09-30 05:43:01;FALSE;"this is my story. first off i wasn't assaulted or raped but i could of been. it was the scariest moment of my life and also one i have never spoken about. i have never told anyone this happened to me until now. i am still scared to share. this past week has made me feel ok with sharing.
while in rosarito for a family wedding years ago
column2: i was almost attacked. it was a great weekend full of love
column3: fun and family and friends. after the wedding while hanging out i decided to go back to my room
column4: late at night (really early morning) alone. it was the one time i wore a dress that was sexier than what i would normally wear & for the first time i felt good in that dress. but walking through the resort

column1: as i was walking down the stairs
column2: i saw a man who was doing the gardening
column3: he made eye contact with me and i felt uncomfortable and started walking faster. he started to follow me and was soon chasing me as i ran across the hotel back yard area. i was scared and all i could think was what if he catches me
column4: & who was in what room incase i needed to scream and knock on a door.

column1: luckily as i turned to where the pool area was
column2: there were people swimming & relaxing in the hot tubs. so the man stopped chasing me & disappeared. i was lucky....

column1: i never spoke of this to anyone because i was ashamed that i wore that red dress & that i chose to walk by myself. i also thought because i was not hurt physically i had no reason to tell anyone. i didn't think anyone would believe me or that i was to blame for my choices.

i thank god i ran fast (in heels!) and for the people in the pool. it could of been worse but it was still scary. and this is my story. #believeher #metoo #strength #whyididnttell #womensupportingwomen #mystory #ibelieveher";;en;#believeher

column1: 337991;instagram;2018-09-30 05:44:52;FALSE;"facts!! as a survivor of rape and multiple molestations... when it's your word against the person who did it the fear you have within you is something you cant describe for an outsider.  it took until i was in my 30's before i admitted to the molestations by family members and babysitters when i was just in elementary school and the rape well the college i went to when i was 18 would have raped me all over again because he was on the prized football team and in one of the black fraternities.  so staying quiet was easier.  my parents and brothers have no clue about any of it.  i dont want to be the reason my dad or my mom has another heart attack. i was a sheltered and overly guarded only daughter and the predators still got to me right under their noses. so take your judgements and shove them up your asses.. yes their are the small few who have lied.. but there are so many of us who have been so afraid to speak up because of things like what is happening in the press now.

column1: 337998;instagram;2018-09-30 05:51:37;FALSE;"me when people ask ""why didn't she say anything sooner?""
let me tell you a story. trigger warning: sexual assault
i haven't really talked about this on the internet before. in 2012
column2: i was sexually assaulted by someone i thought was a friend
column3: in a place i thought i was safe. i thought i was among friends. for the first few minutes
column4: i was frozen from shock. but then i started fighting back. i hit him
column5: i kicked him. i called out to the other friends. and he was made to leave the house.

column2: as i talked to the 2 other friends in the house
column3: i realized they didn't believe me. ""we've known him since childhood
column4: and he would never do something like that."" they wouldn't back me up when i wanted to go to the cops. and they cut me out. i didn't hear from them for a long time.

column2: i hear from one of them. they found out that the guy had done the exact same thing to another girl. and so they believed me. and so my story was valid.

column1: they apologized. and while i have largely forgiven them
column2: it hurts like hell that it needed another woman suffering for them to believe me. that my word wasn't enough. it took me a lot of therapy before i could move on from this. and it still rears its head now and then.
my attacker is married and has a daughter. and i'm petrified for that little girl. i tried to talk to his wife
column3: but she didn't believe me either.

column1: the next time you ask why a woman doesn't speak up when she's assaulted
column2: understand that a lot of times
column3: she tried to. and she was silenced.

column2: listen to women. believe women. and if a woman isn't ready to speak out yet
column3: respect that too. what she's had to go through is hard enough without having to prove that she's going through it.
